response_b:
Here is an example of how to load an image using the Java ImageIO class:
```
import java.awt.image.BufferedImage;
import java.io.File;
import java.net.URL;
import javax.imageio.ImageIO;

public class ImageLoader {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Load image from file
    try {
      File imageFile = new File("image.jpg");
      BufferedImage image = ImageIO.read(imageFile);
      System.out.println("Loaded image from file: " + image.getWidth() + " x " + image.getHeight());
    } catch (IOException e) {
      e.printStackTrace();
    }

    // Load image from URL
    try {
      URL imageUrl = new URL("https://www.example.com/image.jpg");
      BufferedImage image = ImageIO.read(imageUrl);
      System.out.println("Loaded image from URL: " + image.getWidth() + " x " + image.getHeight());
    } catch (IOException e) {
      e.printStackTrace();
    }
  }
}
```
In this example, we use the `ImageIO.read` method to load the image from a file or URL and store it in a `BufferedImage` object. We then print the width and height of the image to the console.

Note that you will need to have the Java ImageIO library included in your project in order to use this method.

Sure! Here are the command line instructions to build an SQLite database for storing the results from your FEM solution:

1. First, create a new SQLite database file named "fem_results.db":
```
sqlite3 fem_results.db
```

2. Create a new table named "node_results" to store the nodal results with columns for node ID, time, water surface elevation (WSE), and discharge (Q):
```
CREATE TABLE node_results (
    node_id INTEGER,
    time REAL,
    WSE REAL,
    Q REAL
);
```

3. Insert the results for each computational node at each time step into the "node_results" table. In this example, we will have 100 nodes and the simulation is 100 seconds long with a time step of 1 second:
```
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (1, 0, 0.0, 0.0);
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (2, 0, 0.0, 0.0);
...
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (100, 0, 0.0, 0.0);
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (1, 1, 0.5, 10.0);
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (2, 1, 0.4, 8.0);
...
INSERT INTO node_results (node_id, time, WSE, Q) VALUES (100, 100, 1.0, 20.0);
```

4. To verify that the results have been successfully stored in the database, you can run a SELECT query to view the contents of the "node_results" table:
```
SELECT * FROM node_results;
```

That's it! You now have an SQLite database set up to store the results from your FEM solution with time series data at each computational node for water surface elevation (WSE) and discharge (Q).

